@@eThe Eastern Desert@@N

Before empires raised pyramids, the eastern waste was managed by
surveyors known as the @@yKeepers of Measure@@N. They ruled not by armies
but by calibration: road stones set to star angles, cistern basins
graded by seasonal drift, caravan levies assessed in @@Wwater rights@@N
rather than coin. The desert was governable if measured correctly.

The @@yTwelve Obelisk Lines@@N were instruments, not monuments. At dawn
and dusk their shadows marked legal travel windows, ration days, and
safe departure periods. Each obelisk face carried glyphs from
@@WMeasure Script@@N -- a writing system where a single symbol encoded
direction, time, water volume, and legal status simultaneously.

As traffic expanded, merchant houses transformed survey law into
hereditary authority: the @@ySalt Ledger Kingdoms@@N, named for the
crystalline tablets used to track water debt. Nobility depended on
logistics legitimacy -- a ruler was accepted only if routes stayed
open and cistern accounts balanced.

The @@rcharter road system@@N connected oasis settlements to pyramid
worksites and distant cities. Charter stones bore distance, toll rates,
and witness seals. Convoy formation rules, ration stamps, and the
night-travel prohibition kept fragile water supplies in balance.

Then the @@dIseth Reach@@N -- the river that fed the eastern corridor --
dried. Water courts became war tribunals. The @@rCharter Wars@@N erupted
as armed factions enforced legal claims at spearpoint. Reaver
confederates who outlasted their employers became the desert's modern
predators, retaining procedural habits: seizure inventories, stamped
claim-slates, and ritualized convoy inspections.

The @@rJackal Synod@@N rose from militarized funerary priesthoods who
seized shrine-cistern nodes and weaponized ritual access to water.
Three rival schools persist: Anointers who preserve any remnant of
old command, Keepers of Dry Mercy who ration suffering rather than
maximize it, and the apocalyptic @@rEclipsed Tongues@@N who seek total
depopulation of the old roads.

Beneath the deepest observatory strata, the @@dLast Sand Regent@@N still
issues decrees to a dead bureaucracy -- a policy engine with royal
memory, governing through desiccation and eclipse while the living
world it claims to protect crumbles to salt and wind.
